        <div type="letter">
            <div type="text">
                <opener>
                    <placeName>Moor Park, Farnham | Surrey</placeName>
                    <date>26<hi rend="superscript">th</hi></date>
                    <salute>Dear Eyton</salute>
                </opener>
                <div type="transcription">
                     
<p>Your letter has been forwarded to me here, where I am staying at a Hydropathic establishment as my health has lately been very indifferent.— I thank you for the reference on Hybrid &amp; for your very kind note.—<ref target="#foot.f2"/> I am delighted to hear what fine Natural History prospect you have before you.—</p>
<p>It is a new &amp; interesting line on the growth of Bones of Birds: I was not at all aware that there was anything peculiar in that subject.<ref target="#foot.f3"/> My confounded health interferes terribly with all my work, but yet I am making steady progress in my Book on Variation of Species. &amp; on domestic varieties.</p>
<p>As you are a great man for Horses, you might aid me, if not irksome to you, by looking out in Ireland or elswhere for any cases of Horses or Ponies with transverse bars on legs like those of zebra, or on shoulder &amp; along the back, as with the ass. These stripes sometimes occur in duns, &amp; mouse-coloured &amp; chesnut horses; &amp; I sh<hi rend="superscript">d</hi>. be infinitely obliged for any cases of this kind.—<ref target="#foot.f4"/></p>
<p>I sh<hi rend="superscript">d</hi>. most thoroughily enjoy visiting you at Eyton; but I am not likely to be in Shropshire soon.—</p>
<p>Pray believe me | Dear Eyton | Yours very truly | C. Darwin</p> 
                </div>
            </div>
                <div type="tnotes">
                    <note xml:id="tnote.n1">1.4 before] <hi rend="italic">before omitted point</hi></note>
                    <note xml:id="tnote.n2">2.2 in] ‘i’ <hi rend="italic">over</hi> ‘o’</note>
                    <note xml:id="tnote.n3">3.2 Ireland] <hi rend="italic">above del</hi> ‘Scotland’</note>
                    <note xml:id="tnote.n4">3.3 the ass.] ‘the’ <hi rend="italic">interl</hi></note>
